As a result of a breach in the visceral or parietal pleura, air enters the pleural space. When the amount of air is large and the increase in intrapleural pressure great, the mediastinum shifts to the opposite side and the diaphragm is depressed (Fig. 48-1
). A decrease in vital capacity, functional residual capacity, total lung capacity, and oxygen transfer occurs.27 In a large pneumothorax, the arterial oxygen pressure (Pao
2) falls and the alveolar-arterial oxygen pressure difference [P(A-a)O2] increases. The factors that lead to hypoxemia during a large pneumothorax are anatomic shunt,28 hypoventilation,29 and relative overperfusion of partially collapsed, underventilated lungs.30 Anthonisen31 reported that in patients with pneumothorax, airway closure occurs at low lung volumes and suggested that this was the main cause of ventilation maldistribution in such patients.
